## 2. IP SLA circular dependency

**Symptom:** SLA probe showed 0 successes / hundreds of failures from the moment it was created; track object Down; router permanently failed over to the backup ISP despite the primary being healthy.

**Root cause:** the probe target (ISP1's loopback) was reachable only via the default route — the same default route the probe's track object controls. Track down -> route withdrawn -> probe has no path -> probe can never succeed -> track can never come back up. The monitor depended on the thing it was monitoring.

**Fix:** one untracked static host route to the probe target (`ip route 100.64.100.1 /32 -> ISP1 next-hop`), giving the probe a path that exists independently of anything it controls.

**Lesson:** monitoring infrastructure must never depend on the object it governs. The probe still tests real path health — if the path beyond the first hop dies, the loopback is unreachable regardless of the host route. Only the bootstrap was fixed.

